description:
secretx-systemd/src/lib.rs:209, 230, 250 use:

    let dir = tempfile::tempdir().unwrap();

so the tempdir is cleaned up automatically when 'dir' drops, even if the test panics. The sibling secretx-file crate (lib.rs:302-305 and similar) rolls its own:

    let path = std::env::temp_dir().join(format!("secretx-file-test-{}", std::process::id()));
    ...
    let _ = std::fs::remove_file(&path);

That pattern leaks files on test failure (the cleanup line never executes if the test panics before reaching it) and is collision-prone if the same PID re-runs the test (e.g. cargo nextest with reused workers).

Defend secretx-systemd's use of tempfile against any future 'remove the tempfile dev-dependency' suggestion. The dev-dep is cheap; the cleanup correctness it buys is worth more than zero.
